@NODE "Twisted MagicWB" "4.1. Twisted Magic Workbench."

 @{b}4.1. Twisted Magic Workbench.
 -----------------------------@{ub}

 It features @{b}27 twisted AGA pictures@{ub} for use with your workbench as a
 background. Look at it this way: instead of that boring grey screen you
 now get a twisted picture with a @{b}REAL FULL AGA copperlist@{ub}. This is
 generated by a tiny program called @{b}`Magic Copper'@{ub}, which you can find in
 the `Misc' drawer of this package. Remember: @{b}you need a 16 COLOUR
 workbench!@{ub}

 Get it now from @{b}Aminet@{ub} in the `@{b}pix/mwb@{ub}' directory.
 The filename is "@{b}TwistedMagicWB.lha@{ub}".

@ENDNODE



@NODE "Twisted MagicWB HTML" "4.2. Twisted Magic Workbench Documentation in HTML Format."

 @{b}4.2. Twisted Magic Workbench Documentation in HTML Format.
 ----------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

 It's nice to see all the backgrounds immediately and that's possible in
 the HTML format.

 Get it now from @{b}Aminet@{ub} in the `@{b}pix/mwb@{ub}' directory.
 The filename is "@{b}TwistedHTML.lha@{ub}".

@ENDNODE



@NODE "Twisted MagicWB Addendum" "4.3. Twisted Magic Workbench Addendum."

 @{b}4.3. Twisted Magic Workbench Addendum.
 --------------------------------------@{ub}

 So, what is this sh#t? Well, it's no shit, I can tell you. It's not just
 another collection of @{"MagicWB" LINK "What is MagicWB 2.0?"} icons. NO WAY! This is a usefull collection
 of icons. Sure, other packages released are nicely done. They have many
 icons but I hardly ever needed those icons. So, I decided to scan my
 hard drive for any old icons and repaint them myself into cool @{"MagicWB" LINK "What is MagicWB 2.0?"}
 icons. The result is visible in this release.

 It features: * @{b}fourty-five image drawers@{ub}, found in the`ImageDrawers'
                directory;
              * @{b}thirty-six program icons@{ub}, found in the `Misc' directory;
              * @{b}some replacement icons for your SYS: partition@{ub}, found in
                the `Prefs', `System', `Utilities' and `WBStartup'
                drawers;
              * @{b}a useless chapter where every icon is discussed seperately!@{ub}

 Get it now from @{b}Aminet@{ub} in the `@{b}pix/mwb@{ub}' directory.
 The filename is "@{b}TMWBAddendum.lha@{ub}".

@ENDNODE



@NODE "Twisted MagicWB Addendum HTML" "4.4. Twisted Magic Workbench Addendum Documentation in HTML Format."

 @{b}4.4. Twisted Magic Workbench Addendum Documentation in HTML Format.
 -------------------------------------------------------------------@{ub}

 Well this is just a cool addition to this package for all the HTML freaks
 out there -- if there are any 8).

 Get it now from @{b}Aminet@{ub} in the `@{b}pix/mwb@{ub}' directory.
 The filename is "@{b}AddendumHTML.lha@{ub}".

@ENDNODE



@NODE "Alot of AGuide icons" "4.5. Alot of Amiga-Guide icons."

 @{b}4.5. Alot of Amiga-Guide icons.
 -------------------------------@{ub}

 This time I decided polish up all the old Amiga-Guide icons still sitting
 there on my hard drive. I repainted them all to fit the new design that
 was released in "Roman's @{"Magic WB" LINK "What is MagicWB 2.0?"} Icons 8" package (get it, it's real
 artwork! It's somewhere on the aminet named `RomIcons8.lha'.)
 Now what do you get:

            * @{b}66 (sixty-six!) Amiga-Guide icons@{ub} according
              to the design mentioned above. (Isn't that just great?
              All your Guide icons, at least most of them, will
              now be in the cool `Roman'-design);
            * @{b}IconUpdate@{ub}, a proggie to easily install these icons
              without losing your tooltypes and preseving the
              position of the icons.

 Well, "this is just some cut, copy and paste work" you say. Indeed it is
 but if nobody does it, then the icons won't start making themselves now,
 will they 8). So, I just took the initiative and in this package, the
 result of a few days of work is clearly visable 8).
 Mind you though, I did create some of these Guide icons myself.

 Get it now from @{b}Aminet@{ub} in the `@{b}pix/mwb@{ub}' directory.
 The filename is "@{b}AlotOfAGI.lha@{ub}".

@ENDNODE



@NODE "What is MagicWB 2.0?" "5. What is MagicWB 2.0?"

 @{b}5. What is MagicWB 2.0?
 -----------------------@{ub}

 This is what @{b}you@{ub} have always been looking for. It is @{b}not@{ub} "just another
 useless Icon compilation"! It is far more different. Please, read on:

 The package contains @{b}all standard System-Icons@{ub} and more (actually
 200 different Icons) painted in a new completely different style: They
 look very 3-dimensional, have @{b}8 colors@{ub}, have @{b}gradient fills@{ub}, feature
 @{b}click-and-push animation@{ub} if being clicked onto to simulate a pushed
 button and even more... To sum it up: They are simply magic!

 MagicWB invents a new standard for the AMIGA Workbench: Now,
 also the drawer Icons will get individual images wherever possible.
 Your SYS: partition will get these new Image-Drawers per default
 when installing MagicWB. Furthermore MagicWB provides @{b}over 50
 Image-Drawers@{ub} for your individual use on other partitions. This
 enables a very nice diversified look on your Workbench screen.

 Second, you will find @{b}52 Background-Patterns@{ub} for your Workbench,
 also designed with the same 8 colors as the Icons. And as a bonus
 you will find four beautiful AGA-Patterns which you can use in con-
 junction with Magic Copper. They give your Workbench the look of a
 workstation with over 16,8 million colors. Simply magic...

 Furthermore the package contains @{b}9 different fonts@{ub} as a replacement
 for the most wanted WB-Fonts Helvetica, Courier and Topaz. These
 new Fonts have been intensively tested to provide the @{b}best readability@{ub}
 for your WB and to finally make the old (horrible) fonts obsolete.
 The fonts are @{b}complete@{ub}, i.e. ALL 256 characters are included in each
 font. Even symbols for control chars were added to these fonts.

 And with MagicWB you will have full @{b}Dock-Icons@{ub} support. Dock-
 Images are a very professional way of activating certain applications
 or complex environments via batch files. MagicWB 2.0 provides you
 with @{b}56 Dock-Images@{ub} for all needs. This makes the AMIGA look as
 professional as for example NeXT workstations.

 Programs like 'MagicWB-Demon' (which cares for the colors and
 patterns), 'IconUpdate' (for quickly converting old Icons to MagicWB-
 Icons) and several scripts (like the powerful new 'Update Drawers') will
 provide you with a full MagicWB support and complete this package.

 Finally the package includes an intelligent, interactive @{b}Installer@{ub} with
 which you don't have to worry about manually installing more than 300
 different files in their respective drawers.

 Why not @{"register" SYSTEM /Extras/MagicWBRegistration}?

@ENDNODE



@NODE "About the author." "7. About the author."

 @{b}7. About the author.
 --------------------@{ub}

 If you've read the guide of @{"my other packages" LINK "Previous releases"} you'll know there is not
 much to say about myself.
 My setup hasn't changed since:

    * an A1200 with 3.1 ROM and a tower case;
    * a `HP DeskJet 520';
    * a mighty `Microbotics A1230' accelerator with a 68030 CPU and MMU
      at 50 MHz, a 68882 coprocessor, also running at 50 MHz plus an
      additional 16 megabytes of 60 nanoseconds fast RAM;
    * two 3.5" external `Cumana' diskdrives;
    * a `Mitsumi' dual speed CD-ROM drive with IDE interface;
    * 1275 megabytes of `Conner' hard drive space;
    * an `Alfa Data' trackball;
    * a `MicroVitec' multysinc monitor (dunno which type, can't find it
      anywhere, not even in the manual!);
    * a pair of 80 watts `Trust - Soundwave 10' loudspeakers;
    * two `Arcade' joysticks and a `Gravis Game Pad'.

 If you have any questions, requests or require more information about
 something (I simply cannot imagine what that might be) just write me
 on the following adress:

  Korneel Ketelslegers
  Dautenstraat 58
  3590 Diepenbeek
  Belgium

 or leave an e-mail to crisp@tornado.be and mention that it is for me
 (Korneel Ketelslegers).

 Be see'n ya!

